To create a web app that connects to an IRC server using WebSockets, handles basic IRC commands, and displays a rank dashboard for the beans score, you can use the following HTML code. This code includes embedded CSS for styling and JavaScript for connecting to the IRC server, handling messages, and updating the display.

Below is a single HTML file that accomplishes what you've described:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Beans Score Dashboard</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }
        #dashboard {
            background: #fff;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }
        #output {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 10px;
            background: #eaeaea;
            border-radius: 5px;
            overflow-wrap: break-word;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="dashboard">
        <h1>Beans Score Dashboard</h1>
        <button id="fetchBeans">Get Beans Score</button>
        <div id="output"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const serverUrl = 'wss://irc.h4ks.com:8097';
        const channel = '#bots';
        const nick = 'your_nickname'; // Replace with your desired nickname.

        const ws = new WebSocket(serverUrl);
        ws.onopen = () => {
            console.log("Connected to the server");

            // Send the NICK and USER commands
            ws.send(`NICK ${nick}`);
            ws.send(`USER ${nick} 0 * :${nick}`);
            ws.send(`PONG ${serverUrl}`);

            // Join the channel
            ws.send(`JOIN ${channel}`);
        };

        ws.onmessage = (event) => {
            const message = event.data;

            // Check for .topbeans command response from _cloudbot
            if (message.includes('_cloudbot') && message.includes('Beans:')) {
                displayOutput(message);
                leaveChannel();
            }
        };

        function displayOutput(message) {
            document.getElementById('output').innerText = message;
        }

        function leaveChannel() {
            ws.send(`PART ${channel}`);
            ws.send(`QUIT :Disconnecting`);
            setTimeout(() => {
                ws.close();
            }, 1000);
        }

        document.getElementById('fetchBeans').onclick = () => {
            ws.send('.topbeans');
        };
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
- **WebSocket Connection**: The script establishes a WebSocket connection to the IRC server.
- **NICK and USER Setup**: The bot sets its nick and user on the server upon connection.
- **Join Channel**: Automatically joins the specified channel (`#bots`) after connecting.
- **Command Handling**: Upon clicking the "Get Beans Score" button, it sends the `.topbeans` command.
- **Output Handling**: It listens for messages containing the response from the `_cloudbot` and will display the output. It then leaves the channel and disconnects from the server.
- **Styling**: Basic CSS is included for layout and aesthetics.

### Note:
- Make sure to replace `your_nickname` with a valid nickname you want to use on the IRC server.
- This code is a basic example. Depending on the IRC server's implementation, you might need to handle more specific server messages and responses.
- Ensure that you have permission to connect and send commands to the IRC server.

