Here's the complete code for your web app:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Beans Score Dashboard</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            color: #333;
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
            justify-content: center;
            height: 100vh;
            margin: 0;
        }
        #dashboard {
            background: #fff;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }
        #output {
            margin-top: 20px;
            padding: 10px;
            background: #eaeaea;
            border-radius: 5px;
            overflow-wrap: break-word;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="dashboard">
        <h1>Beans Score Dashboard</h1>
        <button id="fetchBeans">Get Beans Score</button>
        <div id="output"></div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const serverUrl = 'wss://irc.h4ks.com:8097';
        const channel = '#bots';
        const randomNumber = Math.floor(Math.random() * 10000);
        const nick = `_robot_bean_score_fetcher_${randomNumber}`;

        const ws = new WebSocket(serverUrl);

        ws.onopen = () => {
            console.log("Connected to the server");

            // Send the NICK and USER commands
            ws.send(`NICK ${nick}`);
            ws.send(`USER ${nick} 0 * :${nick}`);
            ws.send(`PONG ${serverUrl}`);

            // Join the channel
            ws.send(`JOIN ${channel}`);
        };

        ws.onmessage = (event) => {
            const message = event.data;

            // Check for .topbeans command response from _cloudbot
            if (message.includes('_cloudbot') && message.includes('Beans:')) {
                displayOutput(message);
                leaveChannel();
            }
        };

        function displayOutput(message) {
            document.getElementById('output').innerText = message;
        }

        function leaveChannel() {
            ws.send(`PART ${channel}`);
            ws.send(`QUIT :Disconnecting`);
            setTimeout(() => {
                ws.close();
            }, 1000);
        }

        document.getElementById('fetchBeans').onclick = () => {
            ws.send('.topbeans');
        };
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Key Changes:
1. **Dynamic Nickname**: The nickname now dynamically includes a random number between 0 and 9999, ensuring it's unique each time the web app runs.
2. **Overall Structure**: The HTML structure and JavaScript functionality remain the same, focusing on connecting to the IRC server, joining the channel, and fetching the beans score.

### Usage:
- Save the code above into an HTML file (e.g., `beans_score_dashboard.html`).
- Open the file in a web browser.
- Click the "Get Beans Score" button to interact with the IRC server and see the output for the `.topbeans` command.

Make sure to verify that the IRC server allows you to connect with this format and to test the application in your environment.
